  "text": "Segmental infarction shares a common etiology and time frame with renal artery thrombosis and may also manifest clinically as graft dysfunction [CITATION_1] . Anatomic lesions such as an atheroma in the renal artery, surgical trauma, and the suturing technique used all may cause thromboembolism at the level of the segmental arteries, especially in the setting of hypercoagulability [CITATION_2] . Renal infarcts may appear as peripheral wedge-shaped defects with no radiotracer activity in all phases of renal transplant scintigraphy (Fig  7; Movie 13 [online] ).",
